{{refimprove|auto=yes|date=December 2009}}
'''Aulic titulature''' is a term, derived from the Greek ''aulè'' and Latin [[wikt:aula#Latin|aula]] (in the meaning ''palace'') for hierarchic systems of titles specifically in use for court protocol.

==Hellenistic antiquity==
Ironically in the formal "court" titulature of the [[Hellenistic]] empires ruled by dynasties we know as [[Diadoch]]s, the title ''diadochos'' was not customary for the Monarch, but has actually been proven to be the ''lowest'' in a system of official rank titles, known as aulic titulature, conferred - ex officio or nominatim - to actual courtiers {{em|and}} as an honorary rank (for protocol) to various military and civilian officials. 

Notably in Lagid Egypt, diadochos was reported as the lowest aulic rank, under ''philos [basilikos]'' ("friend [of the king]"), ''archisomatophylax'' ("arch-bodyguard"), ''protos philos'' ("first friend"), ''homotimos'' ("[nearly] equal dignitary") and ''syggeneus'' ("cognate of the crown"), during the reign of [[Ptolemaios V Epiphanes]]. A similar system of titles was in place in other Hellenistic monarchies. In the Ptolemaic court, the aulic titulature is also distinguished from the titles awarded ''honoris causa''<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|title=Courts and Elites in the Hellenistic Empires: The Near East After the Achaemenids, c. 330 to 30 BCE|last=Strootman|first=Rolf|publisher=Edinburgh University Press|year=2014|isbn=9780748691265|location=Edinburgh|pages=166}}</ref> since several are determined by ''aulic'' functions such as the [[Chamberlain (office)|chamberlain]] or the master of the hunt. 

Scholars describe the ''aulic titulature'' as a complex system and that the meanings of the many known titles within it are unknown.<ref name=":0" /> One approach of understanding it is through the view that it is a form of formalised informality where a ''philos''<nowiki/>' power position, for instance, at court was indicated by his title and not necessarily fixed by it.<ref name=":0" /> While the [[Hierarchy|hierarchisation]] in the court titulature and the status differentiation is seen as advantageous to the king, it is also believed to be an instrument for the top of the court society to close their ranks as they jockey for positions and privileges.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Royal Courts in Dynastic States and Empires: A Global Perspective|last=Duindam|first=Jeroen|last2=Artan|first2=Kunt|last3=Metin|first3=Tülay|publisher=BRILL|year=2011|isbn=9789004206229|location=Leiden|pages=86}}</ref> It is commonly supposed that the institution of a system of court ranks and titles was intended to reinforce the bond between the monarch and his ministers by playing on the vanity of the courtiers.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Cambridge Ancient History|last=Astin|first=A.E.|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1982|isbn=9780521234450|location=Cambridge|pages=165}}</ref> There are also accounts that show how the distribution of ''aulic'' titles served as a form of gift exchange and that the recipient was awarded gifts such as purple clothing, crowns, and horse trappings in order to show his rank or to derive his status from.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com.ph/books?id=O0E_LZdgFVwC&pg=PT77&dq=Aulic+titulature+is&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjps_2J4NLeAhUIUt4KHaglCvYQ6AEIRDAF#v=onepage&q=Aulic%20titulature%20is&f=false|title=A Companion to Ancient Greek Government|last=Beck|first=Hans|date=2013-01-22|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|year=|isbn=9781118303177|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref> 

